  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Towards long-term sustainable change for Street Children 2011</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Nyanza province in Kenya has a HIV prevalence rate that is double the national figure. It also has more than half a million orphans. Poverty, the impact of HIV and AIDS, harmful traditional practices and the 2008 post-election violence have resulted in a high number of children from Nyanza and neighbouring provinces moving to the streets for survival. Many of the children eke out a living working in the shadow economy in deplorable conditions. They lack food, health care, education and shelter and are frequently abused, raped and harassed by community members, police and older children. This project will provide children with access to short-term facilities such as health care, counselling and non-formal education, pending reintegration with their families. The project will also work with government and communities to improve support to street children and stem the flow of children to the streets.</narrative>
  </description>
